    <section1 id="sProp">
        <secTitle>Proper Names</secTitle>
       <p contentType="ctPracticalIntro">
          <content>Proper names are a special kind of noun or phrase that acts syntactically just like other nouns or nominal phrases.</content>
       </p>
       <p contentType="ctComparativeIntro">
            <content>Proper names are a special kind of noun or phrase that acts syntactically just like other nouns or nominal phrases.  In English, some proper names can stand alone, like </content>
            <langData>Sue</langData>
            <content> and </content>
            <langData>Russia</langData>
            <content>.  Others are like compound nouns, such as </content>
            <langData>George Washington</langData>
            <content>.  Proper names may also contain articles and/or </content>
            <case element="pp" attr="pPos">
                <caseText value="before">prepositional</caseText>
                <caseText value="after">postpositional</caseText>
                <caseText value="both">prepositional or postpositional</caseText>
                <caseText value="unknown">adpositional</caseText>
            </case>
            <content> phrases, as in </content>
            <langData>the United States of America</langData>
            <content>.  Many languages require an article before a name.  Appositives also occur, possibly including a possessor, as in </content>
            <langData>my son, David</langData>
		   <content>, but these will be handled later in section </content><sectionRef sec="sCoordAppositive"/><content>.  In addition, proper names can be modified by adjectives and relative clauses, as in </content>
            <langData>the good, old USA</langData>
            <content> or </content>
            <langData>the Susan Welch that I know</langData>
            <content>.</content>
        </p>
       <p show="swClassifiersYesPropYes"><content>In </content><langName/><content>, proper names carry classifiers just like nouns as part of the concord agreement system.</content></p>
       <p show="swClassifiersYesPropNo"><content>In </content><langName/><content>, proper names do not carry classifiers as nouns do as part of the concord agreement system.</content></p>
       <p show="swNPArtAndDemNotNo"><content>Proper names in </content><langName/><case element="prop" attr="pnDeterminer">
          <caseText value="none"> may not</caseText>
           <caseText value="no"> may but are not required to</caseText>
           <caseText value="yes"> must</caseText>
       </case><content> contain </content><case element="np" attr="artAndDem">
          <caseText value="article">an article</caseText>
          <caseText value="demonstrative">a demonstrative</caseText>
          <caseText value="both">an article and/or demonstrative</caseText></case><content> or a possessor.</content></p>
